definition.value: A mixture consisting of a combination of metals or of a metal and another element that retains the characteristics of a metal.
Any alloy composed of platinum and iridium.
An N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of N-hexadecanoylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A monoterpenoid indole alkaloid with forumula C21H26N2O3, isolated from the fruits of Tabernaemontana heyneana.
A fatty acid ester obtained by condensation of the carboxy group of pentadecanoic acid with the hydroxy group of methanol.
A fatty acid methyl ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of 12-methyltetradecanoic acid (12-methylmyristic acid) with methanol.
A nicotine N(1')-oxide resulting from the oxidation of the pyrrolidine nitrogen of (S)-nicotine; major species at pH 7.3.
An (S)-nicotine N(1')-oxide in which the N(1')-methyl group is on the opposite side of the pyrrolidine ring to the pyridine substituent. The major species at pH 7.3.
An (S)-nicotine N(1')-oxide in which the N(1')-methyl group is on the same side of the pyrrolidine ring as the pyridine substituent. The major species at pH 7.3.
A two-electron reduction of this compound results in CHEBI:9260
A four-electron reduction will result in CHEBI:9260
An organic nitrogen anion resulting from the deprotonation of the N-acylsulfonamide moiety of asulam. The conjugate base of asulam.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of (16R)-deshydroxymethyl-stemmadenine.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of (16S)-deshydroxymethyl-stemmadenine.
An organic sodium salt obtained by formal reaction of equimolar amounts of azulam and sodium. A dihydropteroate synthase inhibitor, it is used as a herbicide (mainly for killing bracken).
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of O-acetyl-15alpha-stemmadenine. The major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion resulting from the protonation of the tertiary amino group of 15alpha-stemmadenine. The major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonium ion resulting from thr protonation of the tertiary amino group of catharanthine.

A triazinoindole that is 5H-[1,2,4]triazino[5,6-b]indole which is substituted at position 3 by a (2-methylprop-2-en-1-yl)thio group. A potent inhibitor of midasin which is an essential protein for eukaryotic ribosome biogenesis.
Any heterotricyclic compound whose skeleton consists of an indole fused to a triazine ring.
An N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of N-dodecanoylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of N-(9Z,12Z,15Z)-octadecatrienoylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
Any glycosyloxyflavone that consists of a flavonol attached to a glycosyl residue at position 3 via a glycosidic linkage.
An N-acylglycinate that is the conjugate base of N-decanoylglycine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acylglycinate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-octanoylglycine. The conjugate base of N-octanoylglycine; major species at pH 7.3.
A fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of octanoic acid with ammonia.
A fatty amide of hexanoic acid.
A fatty amide resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of alpha-linolenic acid with ammonia.
A deoxyketohexose that is keto-D-fructose that is lacking the hydroxy group at position 3. A metabolite of 3-deoxyglucosone, a dicarbonyl sugar synthesised through the Maillard reaction.
A D-glucuronate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of aldehydo-D-glucuronic acid; the major species at pH 7.3.
A carboxylic acid anion obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group of any N-acyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycine.
A ceramide in which the fatty acyl group contains 24 carbons and 2 double bonds.
An N-acyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycinate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-hexanoyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycine. The major species at pH 7.3.
A tricarboxylic acid trianion resulting from the deprotonation of all three carboxy groups of(2Z)-4-oxobut-2-ene-1,2,4-tricarboxylate, The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycinate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-octanoyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycine. The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycinate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-decanoyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycine. The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycinate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-dodecanoyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycine. The major species at pH 7.3.
An N-acyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycinate resulting from the deprotonation of the carboxy group of N-tetradecanoyl-(2S)-hydroxyglycine. The major species at pH 7.3.
